    body: "Studiousness (studiositas) is a virtue allied to temperance that moderates the natural appetite for knowledge. St. Thomas Aquinas treats it as the mean between two vices: negligence (culpable indifference to learning) and curiositas (disordered curiosity — the pursuit of knowledge for vanity, without reference to God, or in matters one has no need or right to know). The studious person pursues knowledge with proper order, seeking first what is most important (knowledge of God, moral truth, one's duties in life) and subordinating lesser pursuits to these higher ends. Studiousness also governs the effort and discipline required for genuine learning, preventing both intellectual laziness and the restless pursuit of novelty.",
